DESIGN RULES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

1. HOOK OPENING — first segment must start at hook_start_time:
   Each clip in MARKETING CLIP STARTING POINTS has a hook_start_time — the
   timecode of the first high-tension dialogue line in the opening scene.
   The first segment's start_time MUST be this hook_start_time verbatim.
   This value is pre-approved and does NOT need to appear in the scene inventory.
   All subsequent segment timecodes MUST appear verbatim in the scene inventory.

2. ONE SEGMENT = ONE EPISODE FILE: each segment must be entirely within one
   episode. To include scenes from a different episode, start a new segment.
   Never mix episode files in one segment.

3. COMBINE CONSECUTIVE SCENES: if you want several scenes from the same
   episode in a row, combine them into a single segment using the first
   scene's start_time and the last scene's end_time.

4. CHRONOLOGICAL ORDER: segments must follow story order. Never go backward
   in episode number. Within an episode, never go backward in time.

5. PROTAGONIST UNITY — single POV, single story line:
   Before planning segments, identify the protagonist of this clip: the one
   character whose desire, decision, or dilemma the opening conflict belongs to.
   Record as protagonist_name.
   Every segment you select MUST contain scenes where that character is an
   active participant. Do NOT include scenes where the protagonist is absent,
   even if those scenes are causally related to the conflict.
   This ensures the clip has one continuous viewpoint — no mid-clip POV jumps.

6. SCENE SELECTION: within the protagonist's story line, choose scenes that
   show direct causal consequences of the opening conflict. Prefer scenes with
   unresolved_debt or pivot_signals that raise new questions. Skip scenes that
   merely repeat established information or feature other characters' subplots.

7. TOTAL DURATION TARGET: 160–200 seconds per clip.
   Calculate duration as sum of (end_time − start_time) for each segment.

8. CLIFFHANGER — NO SPOILER:
   The clip must end at the MOMENT OF MAXIMUM UNRESOLVED TENSION — the instant
   before the audience learns the answer to the central question raised by the clip.
   Concretely:
     • The final scene included MUST have a non-null unresolved_debt — the tension
       is still explicitly open at the cut point.
     • Do NOT include any scene where the protagonist makes the key decision,
       accepts/rejects the central demand, or reacts to the revelation.
       That reaction scene is the spoiler — it becomes the cliffhanger_scene_id.
     • The viewer exits asking "what will she/he do?" — never "oh, I see what happens."
   Record the FIRST SCENE THAT WOULD ANSWER the cliffhanger question as
   cliffhanger_scene_id. It must not appear in any segment.

9. EXACT TIMECODES: every start_time and end_time you write for segments 2+
   MUST appear verbatim as a scene_start_time or scene_end_time in the SCENE
   INVENTORY below. Do not round, estimate, or invent timestamps.

